	The New York Times has found that official tallies in the United States and in other countries around the world have undercounted deaths during the coronavirus outbreak because of limited testing availability.




	The New York Times is engaged in a comprehensive effort to track the details of every coronavirus case in the United States, collecting information from federal, state and local officials around the clock. The numbers in this article are being updated several times a day based on the latest information our journalists are gathering from around the country. The Times has made that data public in hopes of helping researchers and policymakers as they seek to slow the pandemic and prevent future ones.



	See our maps tracking the coronavirus outbreak around the world.











	Some businesses are back open.



	Commerce has started to resume in pockets of the country, even as the virus continues to spread. . Restaurants in Alaska were allowed to host some dine-in customers. Students in Montana could return to class as early as next month. And in hard-hit Georgia, the Republican governor allowed a range of businesses, including tattoo parlors and bowling alleys, to reopen despite pushback from public health officials and President Trump.



	Though many called the return to business premature, even dangerous, state and local officials elsewhere have planned to start gradual reopenings of their own in the coming days. And in places where lockdowns remain in place, including in Wisconsin and Kansas, protesters have gathered to state their displeasure with the continuing restrictions.



	In much of the country, case numbers remain high and officials have warned that reopening may still be weeks away. The counties that include Los Angeles and Chicago added more than 1,000 new cases on several recent days. In Massachusetts, case numbers surpassed 58,000 on Tuesday, up nearly 17,000 in just one week.



	But the partial resumption of public life comes amid encouraging signs in other regions. In New York, the governor predicted the worst was over. In Vermont and Hawaii, cases are decreasing. And in New Orleans, where hundreds of infections were being announced each day in early April, only a few dozen per day are being reported now.



	In South Dakota, where residents were never ordered to stay home, Gov. Kristi Noem released what she called a “Back to Normal” plan on Tuesday. It left open the possibility of students returning to class before the end of the academic year and gave businesses suggestions on reopening.



	“In addition to the health costs, the social costs of this virus are historic in the worst way,” Ms. Noem said in a statement.



	Case numbers spike in Midwestern meatpacking cities



	Across the Midwest and Great Plains, production at meatpacking plants and other food processing centers has slowed or stopped because of large outbreaks, including one at a Smithfield facility in South Dakota that sickened more than 1,000 people.



	The Times has confirmed coronavirus clusters in more than 40 food processing facilities across the country. Thousands of workers and their close contacts have been infected. Those numbers are almost certainly an undercount. Some companies, including Smithfield, have refused to provide even basic information about the size of their outbreaks. And in some states, health departments have also declined to give that information.












