                  hydrate: !component,
                  props
                });
              });
            });





	Some agencies and facilities have refused to release the numbers of cases or deaths. Nearly 1,400 inmates and guards have tested positive across New York City’s 10 jails, and 13 deaths have been tied to those facilities. The vast majority of the infections and deaths have occurred among correctional officers. Jason Kersten, a spokesman for the New York City Department of Correction, has declined to specify how many cases were associated with each jail.











	Prisons have been overwhelmed by the virus



	The number of infections in prisons has increased rapidly during the past week. There have been more than 16,000 infections in state prison systems, including almost 12,000 inmates who have tested positive. More than 130 inmates have died. The federal prison system has also been hit hard. At least 23 federal inmates with the virus have died, as has at least one federal prison worker.



	Nearly every state prison system has at least one infection among either inmates or staff, suggesting that the problem will become significantly larger during the next several weeks. Fear and pessimism has settled in among inmates. Riots in Kansas and Washington state were led by inmates worried about contracting the coronavirus, prison officials said. The country’s two largest known coronavirus clusters are in Ohio prisons.



	“We’re just waiting for the next person to test positive,” said Elijah McDowell, an inmate in Connecticut.



	During interviews with nearly two dozen inmates across the nation, prisoners say that correctional facilities are responding to the crisis far too slowly. At Wyoming Correctional Facility in Attica, N.Y., Tracy White, 30, said that only workers on the serving line in the prison’s mess hall are required to wear masks covering their nose and mouth.



	“A lot of people are nervous, tense, scared,” Mr. White said.



	Social distancing, he said, is impossible. Beds are placed three feet apart. As Mr. White spoke over a prison telephone, he said another inmate was on another phone less than two feet away. He said he had cleaned the phone as best as he could, but that he was also wearing a sock on his hand to protect himself from germs.



	The New York Times has also spoken with more than three dozen workers and inmates in the federal Bureau of Prisons who have said that federal prisons are ill-prepared for a coronavirus outbreak. Many lack basic supplies, like masks, hand sanitizer and soap. Workers have complained that inmates are still being moved from prison to prison.



	"It shows a lack of concern for the welfare of inmates, staff and their families," said Jose Rojas, an official in the prison workers' union and a teacher at the Coleman prison complex in Sumterville, Fla., where coronavirus cases have begun to emerge. The bureau, he said, is "putting us in danger."



	Detroit and Chicago confront thousands of cases



	Urban areas across the Midwest have now weathered weeks of rising death tolls and uncontained spread. Though conditions have started to improve in some cities, lockdowns remain in place and hospitals remain busy. On Tuesday, the death toll in Detroit reached 988.



	“More than one in 1,000 of our neighbors has died in the last three weeks,” the city’s mayor, Mike Duggan, said recently.



	Even as new hospitalizations dipped in Detroit, much of the region continued to struggle. More than 280 deaths have been tied to the virus in the county that includes Indianapolis. At least 164 deaths and nearly 2,800 cases have been reported in Milwaukee County, Wis.  And in Illinois, officials announced more than 140 new deaths on Tuesday, the most of any day of the pandemic. . More than 19,000 people in Chicago alone have been infected, and more than 800 have died.



	Gov. J.B. Pritzker of Illinois spoke with alarm after a video circulated on social media showing an apparent house party in which large numbers of people were packed closely together. On Monday, the Chicago police said they had cited the homeowner who they believe hosted the gathering.



	“By standing together, not social distancing, many people not wearing masks — you’re literally putting everyone around you in danger,” said Mr. Pritzker, who has ordered Illinoisans to stay at home. “All of those people have violated not only the intention of the order we put out, but also have violated the trust of their friends and family.”



	Black Americans face worse health outcomes



	Across much of the country, African-Americans have been infected with the coronavirus at disproportionate rates.



	In Louisiana, where about one-third of residents are black, 58 percent of coronavirus patients who died have been African-American. In Michigan, where less than 15 percent of residents are black, about 40 percent of those who died from the virus have been. And in Illinois, where white people outnumber African-American residents by a rate of four to one, 772 black people and 877 white people with the virus had died as of Tuesday.



	“We know the cause: centuries of health disparities fostered by systemic divestment in community health,” Representative Robin Kelly, Democrat of Illinois, said on Twitter.



	But a full national picture of the racial impact was clouded by uneven reporting across states and counties. In many places, racial data for a large percentage of patients was unavailable, potentially skewing results. Other states provided no racial data.



	In California, where early reports suggested that the impact of the virus was spread at roughly proportional rates across racial groups, state officials issued a statement recently saying that black people were being hit harder there, too.




















